VALUES
(43, 7, 42, 40, 1, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of David''s Lineage', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus as ''the son of David,'' linking His identity to the prophesied lineage of David. John 7:42 highlights the expectation of the Messiah coming from David''s seed, which is affirmed in Matthew 1:1.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 42, 42, 2, 11, 11, 'out of the town of Bethlehem', 'Connection of Christ''s Birth and David', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Bethlehem as the birthplace of Christ, linking Him to the lineage of David. John 7:42 mentions the prophecy of the Messiah coming from Bethlehem, while Luke 2:11 confirms that Christ was born in the city of David.', 'prophecy', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 43, 43, 9, 16, 16, NULL, 'Division Among the People', 'Both passages emphasize a division among the people regarding Jesus'' identity and actions. In John 7:43, the division arises from differing opinions about him, while in John 9:16, the division is specifically among the Pharisees concerning his miracles and Sabbath observance.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 43, 43, 10, 19, 19, 'there was a division among the people', 'Division Among the People', 'Both passages emphasize the division among the people regarding Jesus. This recurring theme highlights the contentious nature of his teachings and the varied responses they elicited.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 43, 42, 12, 51, 51, 'division', 'Division Among the People', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of division caused by Jesus. John 7:43 illustrates the division among the people regarding Jesus, while Luke 12:51 explicitly states that Jesus brings division rather than peace.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 43, 40, 10, 35, 35, 'division among the people', 'Division and Conflict in Relationships', 'This connection highlights the theme of division among people due to differing beliefs. Both passages emphasize how following Jesus can lead to conflict within familial relationships.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 43, 44, 14, 4, 4, 'division among the people', 'Division Among the People', 'Both passages emphasize division among the people regarding differing beliefs. In John 7:43, the division is about Jesus, while in Acts 14:4, it concerns the apostles and the Jews.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 43, 44, 23, 7, 10, 'division among the people', 'Division Among the People', 'Both passages emphasize division among groups regarding beliefs. In John 7:43, there is a division among the people because of Jesus, while Acts 23:7-10 describes a dissension between the Pharisees and Sadducees over theological differences. This connection highlights the ongoing conflict and division surrounding key religious figures.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 44, 43, 7, 30, 30, 'no man laid hands on him', 'Divine Timing in Arrest Attempts', 'Both passages emphasize that no one laid hands on him, indicating a divine protection over Jesus during attempts to arrest him. The phrase ''no man laid hands on him'' appears in both contexts, underscoring the significance of timing in these events.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 44, 44, 23, 11, 11, 'no man laid hands on him', 'Divine Protection and Witness', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine protection in both passages. In John 7:44, no man laid hands on Jesus, indicating His protection, while in Acts 23:11, the Lord reassures Paul of his mission, suggesting continued divine safeguarding.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 44, 43, 8, 20, 20, 'no man laid hands on him', 'Protection from Harm', 'Both passages emphasize that ''no man laid hands on him,'' highlighting a divine protection over Jesus during his ministry. This connection underscores the theme of timing in Jesus'' mission, as it is noted that his ''hour was not yet come.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 44, 43, 18, 5, 6, 'no man laid hands on him', 'Authority and Response to Jesus', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus in both passages. In John 7:44, the inability of people to lay hands on him contrasts with the powerful response of those who come to arrest him in John 18:5-6, where they fall backward at his declaration.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 44, 44, 18, 10, 10, 'no man laid hands on him', 'Protection from Harm', 'Both passages emphasize divine protection, as seen in the phrase ''no man shall set on thee to hurt thee'' in Acts, paralleling ''no man laid hands on him'' in John. This connection highlights the assurance of safety for those under God''s care.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 44, 44, 27, 23, 25, 'no man laid hands on him', 'Divine Protection in Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine protection in both passages. In John 7:44, no one could seize Jesus, while in Acts 27:23-25, Paul is assured by an angel that he will be safe during his journey.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 45, 43, 7, 32, 32, NULL, 'Connection of Officers Sent', 'Both passages emphasize the action of the Pharisees and chief priests sending officers to take Jesus. The first passage reflects on the officers'' failure to bring him, while the second describes the initial command to do so.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 45, 44, 5, 21, 27, 'Why have ye not brought him?', 'Authority and Arrest of Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the actions of officers responding to the commands of religious leaders. In John, the officers are questioned for not bringing Jesus, while in Acts, they report back after failing to find the apostles in prison, highlighting the ongoing tension between authority and the followers of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 46, 40, 7, 28, 29, 'Never man spake like this man', 'Authority in Jesus'' Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the unique authority of Jesus'' teachings. The officers'' remark about Jesus'' speaking contrasts with the scribes'' teaching style, highlighting the astonishment of the people at His doctrine.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 46, 42, 4, 22, 22, 'Never man spake like this man.', 'Authority of Jesus'' Words', 'Both passages emphasize the remarkable nature of Jesus'' speech. In John, the officers note, ''Never man spake like this man,'' while in Luke, the crowd is amazed at his ''gracious words.'' This connection highlights the impact of Jesus'' words on his listeners.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 46, 43, 7, 26, 26, 'Never man spake like this man', 'Authority of Jesus'' Speech', 'Both passages emphasize the unique authority of Jesus'' words. The officers'' remark about His speaking contrasts with the rulers'' silence, suggesting a recognition of His boldness and potential identity as the Christ.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 47, 43, 7, 12, 12, NULL, 'Deception and Public Opinion', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of deception surrounding Jesus. In John 7:12, some people claim he deceives the people, while in John 7:47, the Pharisees question if others are also deceived.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 47, 47, 6, 8, 8, 'deceived', 'Deception and Truth Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of deception present in both passages. In John 7:47, the Pharisees question the possibility of being deceived, while 2 Corinthians 6:8 refers to being perceived as deceivers despite being true.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 47, 12, 18, 29, 29, 'deceived', 'Deception and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of deception in both passages. In John 7:47, the Pharisees question the possibility of being deceived, while in 2 Kings 18:29, the king warns against being deceived by Hezekiah''s promises.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 47, 14, 32, 15, 15, 'Are ye also deceived?', 'Deception and Trust in God', 'This connection highlights the theme of deception regarding faith in God. Both passages address the idea of being misled, with the Pharisees questioning if others are ''deceived'' and Hezekiah warning against being ''deceived'' by an enemy''s claims about God''s power.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 47, 40, 27, 63, 63, 'Are ye also deceived?', 'Connection of Deception Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of deception present in both passages. The Pharisees question if others are ''deceived,'' while the reference to Jesus as ''that deceiver'' in Matthew underscores the perception of Jesus as misleading.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 47, 43, 9, 27, 34, 'Are ye also deceived?', 'Pharisees'' Deception and Blindness', 'This connection highlights the theme of deception and spiritual blindness. In both passages, the Pharisees question the validity of belief in Jesus, suggesting a refusal to see the truth despite evidence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 48, 43, 12, 42, 42, 'rulers or of the Pharisees believed', 'Belief Among Rulers', 'This connection highlights the contrast in belief among rulers. While John 7:48 questions if any rulers believed, John 12:42 reveals that many did believe but were afraid to confess.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 48, 43, 7, 26, 26, 'rulers', 'Rulers'' Belief in Christ', 'This connection highlights the skepticism of the rulers regarding Jesus. Both passages question the rulers'' understanding and belief in him as the Christ.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 48, 46, 1, 20, 20, 'Have any of the rulers', 'Wisdom and Belief in Christ', 'This connection highlights the contrast between worldly wisdom and belief in Christ. Both passages emphasize the skepticism of the rulers and wise men regarding faith in Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 48, 46, 2, 8, 8, 'rulers or of the Pharisees believed', 'Connection of Belief and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief among rulers. Both passages address the lack of recognition and belief in Jesus by those in positions of authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 48, 24, 5, 4, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Belief and Leadership', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the rulers'' lack of belief in Jesus and the expectation that the great men should know the way of the Lord. Both passages emphasize the failure of leadership to recognize divine truth, suggesting a disconnect between authority and faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
